Description: Just an awesome, awesome guitar! Here's the deal: it looks beautiful; it plays beautiful; it sounds beautiful. The thing even SMELLS beautiful, lol. It's a 2016 "Late 60s" ES-335 TD in what I believe is the "Lightburst" nitro finish (hence the sweet, sweet smell of a Gibson rock and roll machine!). It comes equipped with MHS humbuckers that growl like an angry dog. Or cat. Whatever, to each his own - but the point is they GROWL! And they sing! Has a trapeze tailpiece which is, I think, part of what sold me on it in the first place - there's a certain 'give' to the feel of the strings, and it's a good thing. Actually, to me, a great thing! I'd always found 335s to be wound just a little too stiffly - never liked the action much, hard as I tried. This one with the trapeze tail though . . . whoa! It's like the strings just want to melt into the motion of your hand, and your playing becomes effortless. Okay - YOUR playing, because MY playing is pretty much like what a gorilla would do trying to fix a Swiss watch, but trust me - it plays great. "Okay Mr. Prosey Ebay Posting Dude - if it's so great, why are you letting it go??" "Let me tell you a story, my son. Once upon a time, there was a man - a man who met perhaps the best playing, most beautiful sounding guitar he'd ever seen or heard. And he fell in love with that guitar. But he had . . . FAT FINGERS!!! (cue the diabolical organ music)" Alright, it's not quite that bad, but the deal is this: like the name says, it's a "Late 60s" 335, which means it has a "Late 60s" neck, which is - according to Gibson - a skinnier neck that every other time period Gibson has ever produced 335s and the necks that go with them. I'm not talking skinny from top to bottom - like the difference between a 50s Les Paul and a Slim 60s Les Paul neck; I'm talking skinnier from side to side, from E to shining e. Which, frankly, is just fine. I'm happy to play her and stumble around like I do on every other fretboard, regardless of neck width, but I can see that in the long run, I may never get totally used to it, especially because I find myself gravitating to chunkier necks as I get older. The neck is deep, however - like from top to bottom - which really does make the neck feel like it's NOT a skinny neck. It does have some good real estate to grab on to, you just have to be aware that you're going to have slightly - SLIGHTLY - less room between the strings. Which makes for some really fast runs, but can - like for me - make chording a little more tricky. Anyways, full disclosure. There is one tiny, tiny, tiny little spot on the back of the neck, shown in a photo. It's like a tiny white speck. Not really sure what it is. Might even come off if I give it a try over the weekend, but that is the ONLY flaw I see on this beauty. Ships with original Gibson case. Additional pics will be posted as requested. Boxes, no FPOs, and NO SHIPPING OUTSIDE U.S.A. Thanks for looking!
Title: 2016 Gibson "Late 60s ES-335 TD" - MHS pickups - Original Case
